title HAWM1's Sala witness lands -- Glow's own fold proven for Android's bionic target, half-verified in the jail
prompt After HAWM0's real GREEN boot, asked via AskQuestion which door mattered most next; Keaton chose HAWM1 (build/run the Sala broadcaster client against the real booted AVD) over HAWM2 (real GrapheneOS build) or pausing for physical-Pixel shopping.
think Checked whether Zig genuinely supports Android as a cross-compile target before writing anything that assumed it did -- `zig targets` lists `android`/`androideabi` as real ABI entries, and a throwaway smoke test (`zig build-exe hello.zig -target x86_64-linux-android`) produced a real, statically-linked ELF binary on the first try. This mattered because HAWM1's whole claim depends on Glow's own code actually being compilable for Android's bionic libc, not merely runnable via the same Linux-syscall-compatible qemu-user path M0 already proved for aarch64.
think Chose the same witness M0 already used (`linengrow/sala_session_core_witness.rye`, the Sala B0 claim) rather than writing a new one, so the claim being extended is legible against an already-proven baseline: M0 proved this exact witness cross-builds for aarch64-linux-musl and reproduces its own native session root under qemu-user; HAWM1 asks the parallel question for a real Android device instead of an emulated Linux binary.
think Designed hawm1_sala_witness.rish to prove determinism against a fresh native reference computed in the same run, rather than hardcoding an expected session-root string -- a hardcoded hash would silently go stale the moment the witness's own fixture data changed upstream, while a live native build-and-compare stays correct automatically. Independently re-ran both builds by hand outside the witness first (native and android-target) to confirm the session root really is stable and byte-identical (99b3ae967c5a230acfc598a7e949b3c2c638ce996be47a51a7c9f8cb12e4c5fe, same on every run) before trusting the witness's own comparison logic.
think Named honestly, inside the witness's own header and in every doc touched, exactly which half is verifiable from inside this jail and which needs the host terminal: the two cross-builds (native, android-target) need only Zig and disk, so both ran and were checked right here; the adb push/shell/compare half needs a live `hawm0` emulator, which needs /dev/kvm, which this jail does not have by design. Ran the whole witness inside this jail as a real test anyway, expecting and getting a clean, correctly-worded refusal at the "no emulator attached" assert -- proof the Rish logic, sequencing, and error path are all correct up to the exact boundary this jail cannot cross, the same discipline HAWM0's own entrypoint used last turn.
think Deliberately used /data/local/tmp as the on-device push target rather than any app-private path -- it is the standard, unprivileged, shell-writable location `adb shell` scripts use for exactly this kind of ad-hoc native-binary execution, needing no app install or signing.
obs This closes the same M0-shaped question (does Glow's verified fold survive a target-architecture crossing) for a genuinely different kind of target than M0/M0-riscv ever addressed: not a Linux binary under user-mode QEMU, but a real Android device's own bionic userland, reached by adb rather than a direct exec. The claim is meaningfully stronger once the host-terminal half completes, since it proves compatibility with Android's actual C library, not just its CPU architecture.
file tools/hawm1_sala_witness.rish -- new; cross-builds native + android-target, pushes/execs via adb, asserts session-root equality; run inside this jail and confirmed to refuse correctly at the no-emulator-attached check
file context/specs/two-dev-environments-and-mobile-emulation.md -- stamp line, HAWM1 rung's own State cell rewritten from horizon to "witness written and half-verified," naming exactly what remains
file work-in-progress/TASKS.md -- new dated bullet recording the full witness design, the independent hand-verification of both builds, and the honest jail-vs-host-terminal split
file work-in-progress/ROADMAP.md -- new dated paragraph naming Keaton's own choice of door and the witness landed behind it
recommend check-in only for the literal keystroke Keaton alone can supply -- running `rishi/bin/rishi run tools/hawm1_sala_witness.rish` from the same plain host terminal HAWM0 already used, with `hawm0` still booted (or rebooted via `tools/hawm0_boot_onpath_host.rish` first). Everything upstream of the adb half is real, verified, and done; the witness's own final assert will name plainly whether the session roots actually agree once run against the real device.
